FRANCE,":"Sens sur Seille, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, Frankrijk"},"en":{"18 OCT 1123–11 OCT 1188":"18 October 1123–11 October 1188","1164–1222":"1164–1222","1118–1152":"1118–1152","1185–1234":"1185–1234","1123–1188":"1123–1188","1118":"1118","13 JAN 1152":"13 January 1152","11 OCT 1188":"11 October 1188","1234":"1234","1123":"1123","1222":"1222","1188":"1188","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1152":"1152","27 MAY 1142":"27 May 1142","18 OCT 1123":"18 October 1123","Paris,75056,Paris,Île-de-France,FRANCE,":"Paris, Île-de-France, France","Braine,02110,Aisne,Hauts-de-France,FRANCE,":"Braine, Aisne, Hauts-de-France, France","Dreux, Eure-et-Loir, Centre, France":"Dreux, Eure-et-Loir, France","Sens-sur-Seille,71514,Saône-et-Loire,Bourgogne-Franche-Comté,FRANCE,":"Sens sur Seille, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Dreux","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Channel Islands:  See  Druce  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Druce","meanings":["English: variant of   Drewes  , a surname of French origin.","Possibly an altered form of Dutch and German   Drewes  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert II de Dreux was born on 18 October 1123, in Braine, Aisne, Hauts-de-France, France. He married Hervise de SALISBURY on 27 May 1142, in Sens sur Seille, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, France. He died on 11 October 1188, in his hometown, at the age of 64, and was buried in Braine, Aisne, Hauts-de-France, France."},"et":{"18 OCT 1123–11 OCT 1188":"18. oktoober 1123–11. oktoober 1188","1164–1222":"1164–1222","1118–1152":"1118–1152","1185–1234":"1185–1234","1123–1188":"1123–1188","1118":"1118","13 JAN 1152":"13. jaanuar 1152","11 OCT 1188":"11. oktoober 1188","1234":"1234","1123":"1123","1222":"1222","1188":"1188","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1152":"1152","27 MAY 1142":"27. mai 1142","18 OCT 1123":"18. oktoober 1123","Paris,75056,Paris,Île-de-France,FRANCE,":"Paris, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Braine,02110,Aisne,Hauts-de-France,FRANCE,":"Braine, Aisne, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Dreux, Eure-et-Loir, Centre, France":"Dreux, Eure-et-Loir, Prantsusmaa","Sens-sur-Seille,71514,Saône-et-Loire,Bourgogne-Franche-Comté,FRANCE,":"Sens sur Seille, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"18 OCT 1123–11 OCT 1188":"18. lokakuuta 1123–11. lokakuuta 1188","1164–1222":"1164–1222","1118–1152":"1118–1152","1185–1234":"1185–1234","1123–1188":"1123–1188","1118":"1118","13 JAN 1152":"13. tammikuuta 1152","11 OCT 1188":"11. lokakuuta 1188","1234":"1234","1123":"1123","1222":"1222","1188":"1188","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1152":"1152","27 MAY 1142":"27. toukokuuta 1142","18 OCT 1123":"18. lokakuuta 1123","Paris,75056,Paris,Île-de-France,FRANCE,":"Paris, Île-de-France, Ranska","Braine,0211